    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided financial disclosures and business overview, the **Connectivity segment** (primarily operating under the Starlink brand) generates revenue through a diverse mix of consumer, enterprise, government, and mobile offerings. \n\nHere is the detailed breakdown of the revenue streams, sub-categories, definitions, and accounting policies disclosed in the text:\n\n### 1. Revenue Sub-Categories & Streams\nThe Connectivity segment\'s revenue is disaggregated into the following primary sub-categories:\n\n*   **Consumer Broadband:**\n    *   **Definition:** High-speed, low-latency space-based internet service for residential and rural/remote users. \n    *   **Revenue Stream:** Generated primarily through monthly subscription fees (which vary by geographic market, download speed, and service tier) paired with the one-time sale of hardware (Starlink Kit). \n    *   **Scale:** Consumer subscribers represented over 60% of Connectivity segment revenue in 2025.\n*   **Enterprise:**\n    *   **Definition:** Mission-critical, in-motion, and distributed connectivity environments for businesses, supported by dedicated hardware and tailored commercial structures.\n    *   **Sub-categories:** Includes **Aviation** (broadband for commercial and private aircraft), **Maritime** (global, oceanwide coverage for consumer and commercial maritime use), **Mobility**, and other enterprise businesses.\n    *   **Revenue Stream:** Contracts are structured as a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, capacity, or on a percentage-of-completion basis depending on customer needs.\n*   **Government (Starshield):**\n    *   **Definition:** A secure satellite network designed specifically for government customers and national security applications.\n    *   **Revenue Stream:** Generated via long-term, multi-year contracts.\n*   **Starlink Mobile (Direct-to-Cell):**\n    *   **Definition:** Satellite-to-mobile services enabling existing phones to connect for light data, SMS, and over-the-top (OTT) voice services (e.g., WhatsApp, FaceTime) via the "V1" mobile constellation.\n    *   **Revenue Stream:** Generated through partnerships with approximately 30 Mobile Network Operators (MNOs). The company charges MNOs a fixed fee, a per-mobile-user fee, or earns revenue via revenue-sharing arrangements based on connectivity services included in the MNOs\' consumer plans.\n    *   *Note:* Financial footnotes explicitly state that **Starlink Mobile revenue is included within the "Enterprise & Government" revenue line item**.\n*   **Products vs. Services Breakdown:**\n    *   **Products:** **100% of all "Products" revenue** across the entire company is attributable to the Connectivity segment (representing the sale of Starlink Kits/terminals).\n    *   **Services:** Represents the recurring broadband and mobile connectivity subscription revenues.\n\n### 2. Definitions & Revenue Recognition Policies\nThe company applies specific accounting policies to recognize revenue for its various Connectivity streams:\n\n*   **Broadband & Mobile Services (Over Time):** Revenue for services is satisfied and recognized *over time* as the customer simultaneously receives and consumes the benefits. \n    *   *Consumer Broadband:* Generally month-to-month contracts; revenue is recognized ratably over the subscription term (equal to the amount billed that month).\n    *   *Mobile Connectivity Agreements:* Generally multi-year contractual obligations (ranging from 1 to 5 years), though customers can typically terminate at any time. Recognized based on actual data consumption or ratably.\n*   **Starlink Kits / Hardware (Point in Time):** Revenue for the Starlink Kit (inclusive of the terminal) is recognized *upon delivery* to the customer, or upon installation for certain enterprise customers. It is reported net of sales returns, credits, and discounts.\n*   **Government / Starshield Contracts (Cost-to-Cost):** Revenue for multi-year Starshield contracts is recognized *over time* using the **cost-to-cost input method** (revenue is recorded based on costs incurred to date, such as materials and labor hours, relative to the total estimated cost at completion).\n*   **Multiple Performance Obligations:** Substantially all Starlink customer contracts contain multiple performance obligations (e.g., the broadband service + the Starlink Kit). The transaction price is allocated to each distinct obligation based on its **standalone selling price** (the price at which the good/service is sold separately to similar customers in similar locations). Starlink Mobile services, however, have only one performance obligation.\n\n### 3. Deferred Revenue\n*   **Definition:** Deferred revenue is recorded when cash payments are received or due in advance of the company’s performance.\n*   **Connectivity Impact:** Deferred revenue primarily relates to **Connectivity enterprise and government contracts** (as well as Space agreements). \n*   **Balances:** Total deferred revenue was $10,179 million as of December 31, 2024, and grew to $12,116 million as of December 31, 2025.\n\n### 4. Cost of Revenue (Connectivity Segment)\nTo support these revenue streams, the Connectivity segment incurs the following direct costs:\n*   Depreciation (inclusive of launch, satellite, and ground infrastructure costs)\n*   Starlink Kit (hardware) costs\n*   Shipping, handling, freight, and customs/duties\n*   Ground operating expenses\n*   Employee compensation (engineering and operations teams)\n*   Payment processor fees\n*   Warranty expenses, customer support, and installation costs\n*   Inventory excess and obsolescence',
