untries/territories | No country-level or regional revenue disaggregation for Connectivity |\n\n---\n\n### III. Modeling Limitations Arising From This Disclosure Structure\n\n#### 1. **Inability to Model Unit Economics for Enterprise/Government**\nThe "Starlink Subscribers" KPI (10.3M as of Q1 2026) **explicitly excludes** managed enterprise and government customers. There is no equivalent subscriber or terminal-count metric for enterprise/government. This means:\n- No enterprise ARPU can be calculated\n- No enterprise churn rate is disclosed\n- No terminal deployment count for enterprise/government is available\n- Revenue per enterprise contract or per government program cannot be derived\n\n#### 2. **Hardware Margin Is Unobservable at the Customer-Level**\nProducts revenue ($1,510M in FY 2025) is reported in aggregate, and cost of revenue references a $907M increase in Starlink Kit volume spend in FY 2024. However:\n- The filing does not disclose the **gross margin on hardware** (i.e., whether Starlink Kits are sold at cost, at a loss, or at a profit)\n- The allocation of Products revenue between consumer and enterprise is unknown\n- Analysts cannot determine whether hardware subsidization is a drag on consumer margins or whether enterprise kits carry different pricing\n\n#### 3. **Enterprise & Government Is a "Black Box" With Only Deltas**\nBecause only period-over-period *changes* are disclosed for aviation, maritime, mobile, and government sub-streams:\n- Base-year absolute revenue for each sub-stream must be estimated through cumulative back-calculation from multiple periods, compounding estimation error\n- The mix shift between high-value government contracts (Starshield) and lower-ARPU mobile connectivity cannot be tracked\n- A Q1 2026 government revenue decline of $175M could reflect contract timing, completion of a Starshield milestone, or loss of a program—none of which are distinguishable\n\n#### 4. **ARPU Decline Is Ambiguous**\nARPU fell from $99/month